On 02/02/2020, at 0645 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered OXAX 23166, a loaded tank car of Butyraldehyde, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0202-00013). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve primary flange gasket misaligned and the valve not properly secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Sean Wengler, phone 979-241-4222. Contractor personnel removed the liquid line valve, reinstalled the primary flange gasket, and reinstalled the liquid line valve. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 278 NARRI: 110
column169: (NAR cause Code 278  What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Connection between valve and manway cover plate Why Failed: Connection (mounting) flange gasket misaligned)

column168: At 2230 hrs., while the Rook yard crew was doing switching, they noticed an odor coming from tank car BAPX 222304.  They investigated and found that there was liquid dripping from the bottom outlet valve.  They put a bucket under the valve and called the yardmaster who then called called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I called Specialized Professional Services in Washington, PA to come out and investigate.  It was found that there was a leak at the bottom outlet valve, valve stem packing.  They checked to see if they could tighten the packing in case it was loose.  They were able to get the packing gland to tighten and the leak stopped.  They observed for several minutes to see if it would start to leak again and it did not.  The car was then released into transportation.  NARRI: 2(5+5)x(2+0)=40                                 Cause Code: 547
column169: Periodic checks of the packing gland would be advised.

column168: While working in a trailer at the Veolia ten day intransit facility in Tonawanda, NY, a Veolia employee noticed a small puddle of liquid under a few drums. The employee moved drums and determined there were two 55 gallon drums that had punctures at the bottom edge of the drums. One drum contained nonhazardous material and the other drum contained the UN2735, Waste Amines Liquid, Corrosive,  n.o.s. hazardous waste material. The drum containing the hazardous was the original manufacturer's  packaging and appeared to be in good condition when it was accepted for transportation. The total amount spilled was approximately 2 liquid gallons. The spill was contained within the trailer and was  cleaned up by Veolia employees using absorbent pads, vermiculite and speedy dry. Both of the leaking drums were overpacked into 95 gallon drums so they could be safely shipped with any further incidents. It was determined that the drums became punctured from a drum cart while being loaded onto the  trailer.
column169: To mitigate this type of incident from occurring again Veolia will review the spill in the next weekly  training meeting on 2/19/2020. The importance of inspecting drum carts for jagged or sharp edges will be stressed with the material handler employees.

MATERIAL WAS PURCHASED FOR INSTALLATION ON AN AIRCRAFT IN HEAVY MAINTENANCE. MATERIAL ARRIVED IN CARDBOARD BOARD, WITHOUT THE REQUIRED DG DECLARATION.  AAR CORPORATION VENDOR PURCHASE ORDER: 1669825 PART NUMBER: 30903886 SQUIB (CARTIDGE) QTY. 1 EA REQUESTED VENDOR TO SHIP TO AAR FACILITY IN WINDSOR, ON, CANADA VENDOR MIS-SHIPPED TO AAR CORPORATION IN WOOD DALE, IL, USA FEDEX TRACKING #777725116921. DELIVERED 12-JUL-2020.  KIMBERLY HOLLAND @ AAR HAD BEEN CONTACTED (BY AAR RECEIVING MANAGER JOSE GONZALES) 13-FEB-2020 @ 09:28, AND ADVISED OF THE MIS-SHIP. INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO PAUL KLIMAS @ THE FAA HAZMAT OFFICE. HE ADVISED AAR TO QUARANTINE THE PACKAGE, AND IN TURN, CONTACTED THE LOCAL CHICAGO OFFICE. INSPECTOR ORDE DUPLESSIS MADE A SITE VISIT 13-FEB-2020 @ 12:20. MR. DUPLESSIS TOOK AN ABUDANCE OF PHOTOS, AND ADVISED AAR WOULD BE OKAY TO RE-SHIP THIS, IN THE PROPER SHIPPING CONTAINER, AS NEEDED.
column169: VENDOR WILL BE CONTACTED TO ADVISE OF THE VIOLATION, AND PROPER STEPS REQUIRED.  AAR HAS CREATED AN INTERNAL CORRECTIVE ACTION EVENT (APRISe 248473). THE VENDOR WILL BE GIVEN THE OPPORTUNITY TO INITIATE A CORRECTIVE ACTION & REMEDIATION PLANE. FUTURE VIOLATIONS WILL THREATEN VENDORS "APPROVED" STATUS, WHICH COULD IMPEED AAR'S ABILITY TO PROCURE FROM GOING FORWARD.

column168: On February 18, 2020, at approximately 8:35 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers(RL) at the above-referenced location observed a damaged bulk container on trailer 668041. As a result of the damage, approximately 2 cups of UN1866(resin solution) released to the trailer floor. At approximately 8:43 am CST, a representative with RL retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental GAS) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 10:22 am CST, a crew from TAS arrived on-site. Following a site assesspemtn, TAS personnel noted one(1) 55-gallon drum that was damaged and Leaking resin solution. TAS personnel advised the damage was a small puncture and appeared to not be properly constructed. The damaged drum was overpacked in one(1) poly drum. Crews then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. All resin solution impacted material was collected and containerized in poly overpacked drum. TAS personnel secured the drum on-site and scheduled to return at a later date for transport and disposal.

column168: while the Brewster Yard crew was switching, the remote control engineer, while walking the switching lead, heard Tank car TILX 307286 hissing from on top the car.  He notified the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis hazardous Materials/environmental Officer for the WLE.  I cam out to investigate to find that the Vapor Valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I also found that the valve was not shut tightly.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I them tightened the valve plug which ws only hand tight.  i then checked the liquid valves and although the handles we tight and not leaking, the valve plug were only hand tight so I tightened them with a tool.  I then leased the car for transportation.  During this process, the switching lead has to be shut down to traffic since this car was in close proximity of the lead.   NARRI: 5(4+5+0) x (2+0)=90                                    Cause Code: 379

On 02/01/2020, at 1100 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge Yard discovered GATX 221130, a loaded tank car of Sulfur, Molten, with a strong odor coming from the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0201-000058). Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an improperly installed and torn manway nozzle gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Ms. Lesley Praud, phone 587-774-5998. Contractor personnel removed the damaged gasket, replaced in kind, and secured the manway cover and nozzle. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 209 NARRI: 60

On 02/03/2020, at 1300 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered GATX90875, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0203-00127). Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the top operating bottom outlet valve partially open and the secondary closure cap not containing the release. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Robert Pate, phone 423-336-4011. Contractor personnel secured the operating valve, and properly installed the secondary closure cap. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 707 NARRI: 100

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: From Shelby Police Crash Report:   "Unit 2 was a gasoline tanker that was parked in the parking lot.  Unit 2 had gas hoses ran out and was filling up the underground fuel tanks at the service station.  Unit 1 was parked at a gas pump near where the tanker was sitting.  Unit 1 proceeded forward from the parking space and ran over a hose nozzle (fitting) that was pumping fuel.  This nozzle broke and fuel spilled onto the pavement of the parking lot.    Shelby Fire Department and a private Hazmat team responded and were able to clean up the spill.  No injuries reported."  104 gallons spilled and contained on the concrete spill pad.  No storm drains or groundwater impacted.  Cleanup crew removed all product and residue.

On February 26,2020, a release of UN3289 was discovered at the above-referenced location during unloading and was estimated at 1/4 gallon to the trailer surface. It was requested to mobilize a crew and assist with the cleanup. At approximately.m. CST, a representative with R&L Carriers(R&L) retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from TAS Environmental GAS) to mobilize and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 10:30 a.m. CST, TAS personnel arrived on site and conducted an inspection of the area. Crew members collected four (4) damaged 5-gallon jugs and containerized into one(1) 30-gallon poly drum to be left on site until profiling could be completed. TAS personnel then deployed absorbents and a neutralizing agent to collect any material that was released to the trailer surface. All impacted absorbents and neutralizing agent was collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum to be left on site until profiling could be completed. With the site returned to pre-release conditions, TAS personnel collected all tools and equipment and demobilized from the site.

column168: On February 26,2020, at approximately 9:00 a.m. CST, facility personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers (RLC) location crushed one(1) 1-gallon metal can of paint with a forklift during loading operations. As a result of the damage, approximately one (1) gallon of paint released from the bucket to the palletized cargo. At approximately 7:00 p.m. CST, a representative with RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. ES personnel arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, ES observed approximately one(1) gallon of paint released from one(1) 1-gallon metal can to the palletized cargo. ES removed all impacted cargo from the pallets and containerized the material into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ES rewrapped the remaining cargo for continued use by RLC, then secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: PROX 23130 was found in the Klamath Falls, OR yard to be leaking by an ODOT inspector. A BNSF HazMat responder assessed the car and found a loose "Scully" loading sensor that resulted in the release of vapor from around the threads. The sensor was tool-tightened and the leak subsided. The car had an OTMA granted for movement to destination for unloading and also had "Home Shop" stickers applied to each side to prevent further loading until testing.
column169: The shipper must ensure that these Scully loading devices are tool-tightened to prevent future releases of hazardous materials. (NAR:481)

column168: On 2/5/20, the PROX 31534 was found to be venting a small amount of butane through the vapor valve on the car.  The car was isolated and responders inspected the car finding a loose closure plug on the valve and the valve being partially opened.  Responders closed the valve and secured the plug to a tool tight condition.  It was confirmed that there was no longer a release and the car was allowed to continue in transportation.  Estimated release volume is based upon information provided by responders.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING  NORTHBOUND ON 1 85 NORTH IN GWINNETT COUNTY, GEORGIA. THE CLAIMANT VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A PRIOR COLLISION AND WAS STOPPED IN THE NUMBER TWO LANE ON 1 85 NORTHBOUND. THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT STRUCK THE REAR END OF THE CLAIMANT VEHICLE. THIS APPEARS TO HAVE CAUSED THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE TRUCK AND TANK TRAILER AND ULTIMATELY ROLL OVER ON THE HIGHWAY. THE TANK TRAILER WAS BREACHED ALLOWING SOME OF THE GASOLINE AND DIESEL TO BE RELEASED AND IMPACT NEARBY STORM DRAINS. A LARGE FIRE ALSO RESULTED FROM THE ACCIDENT, BOTH THE  KENAN TRANSPORT LLC DRIVER AND THE DRIVER OF THE CLAIMANT VEHICLE WERE KILLED AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION. THE DEATH CERTIFICATES HAVE NOT BEEN RELEASED AS OF THIS DATE SO IT IS UNKNOWN WHETHER THE INDIVIDUALS PERISHED AS A RESULT OF THE INJURIES SUSTAINED IN THE COLLISION OR THE RESULTING FIRE. HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING AND PROCEDURES.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release. The unit inside of the box containing the lithium battery was packaged incorrectly, There was not enough foam or packaging material to protect the unit from damage.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: On February 28, 2020, at approximately 6:45 a.m. CST, at the above referenced R+L Carriers (RL) terminal, one(1) 55-gallon of xylenes was damaged by a forklift. As a result, approximately one(1) gallon of xylene released to the concrete terminal surface. At approximately 6:13 a.m. CST, a representative from RL retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.((DIES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from US Environmental Services, LLC.(USES) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. Following a site assessment, crews noted approximately two(2) gallons of xylenes released to the concrete terminal surface. USES personnel deployed additional granular absorbents and swept them in using hand tools. Crews overpacked the impacted drum into one(1) 65-gallon drum for transport and disposal. All xylenes impacted material was collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. USES personnel noted no further action required onsite and demobilized.

column168: On February 28, 2020, at approximately 9:10 a.m. CST, at the above referenced R+L Carriers (RL) terminal, one(1) 55-gallon drum of amines liquid corrosive was punctured by a forklift. As a result, approximately three(3) gallons released to the trailer floor and outside the trailer to the concrete surface. At approximately 9:45 a.m. CST, a representative from RL retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC. (ER) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. A crew from ER arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, crews utilized simple green to neutralize the trailer. ER personnel deployed granular absorbents to the amines liquid corrosive impacted concrete surface and swept them in with hand tools. Crews then deployed granular absorbents to the trailer floor and swept them in with hand tools. All amines liquid corrosive impacted material was collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ER personnel overpacked the amines liquid corrosive impacted drum into one(1) 95-gallon drum to be returned to the point of origin. ER personnel noted no further actions required onsite and demobilized.

On 2/21/2020 at around 1325 hours EST, CSXT personnel reported a release from covered hopper car AXLX12956, residue Sodium Hydroxide, Solids, coming from the bottom of the car at MP CA 524 in Russell, KY. The car was isolated and the shipper, Royal Chemical, was notified via Chemtrec and the consignee Axial/ Westlake contacted back. Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found a release coming from a broken/ missing component of the unloading piping on the bottom of the covered hopper car.  Quick Response applied temporary containment/ plugging measures to contain the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee at the request of the shipper (David Diethorn, (412)512-5731, dave.diethorn@westlake.com).  The consignee is in contact with an MRU for order of replacement parts for car repair.  Car remains on hold pending MRU repair.     Russell, KY, AXLX12956, Sodium Hydroxide, Solid

A DRIVER FOR TRUGREEN WAS IN TRANSIT, RETURNING TO TRUGREEN'S FACILITY IN CHARLOTTE, NC, WHEN HIS VEHICLE WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR BY A THIRD-PARTY VEHICLE. APPROXIMATELY SEVENTY (70) GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE MEDIAN AND INTO A STORM DRAIN AT THE SITE. THE STORM WATER UNIT FOR THE CITY OF CHARLOTTE, NC RESPONDED TO THE SITE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND PERFORMED CLEANUP OF THE IMPACTED MEDIAN AND IMPACTED STORM DRAIN. THE SITE WAS SECURED, AND CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL. THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, THE NORTH CAROLINE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT AND NATURAL RESOURCES, AND THE MECKLENBERG COUNTY LEPC. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.

column168: On February 12, 2020, a tractor-trailer docked at the above-referenced location was discovered, during the unloading process, to have damaged one quart cans containing UN1268 (petroleum, cleaning prep liquid). As a result of the damage, approximately 5 gallons of UN1268 was released to the trailer floor. At approximately 1:34 p.m. CST, a representative from R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental(FCE) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 3:22 p.m. CST, a crew from FCE arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, FCE personnel noted approximately 5 gallons of UN1268 released to the trailer floor. FCE personnel applied granular absorbent to the trailer floor, and swept them in with hand tools. FCE drum rolled 76 undamaged cans with UN1268 on the exterior, and containerized in to one 55-gallon drum left with the driver. Eight damaged cans were collected and containerized in to one 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column168: Reporting DGO was notified by CN Waterloo Mechanical Department that tank car PROX 16593 (L-UN 1830; Sulfuric Acid) was found to be leaking from the top.  CN response team was dispatched, finding liquid sulfuric acid leaking from the liquid line flange. The response team found the liquid line bolts were too corroded to remove the flange plates to inspect the gasket. The response team opened the vapor line, which stopped the leak.  The vapor line was left open as to not allow the car to build pressure, while the liquid line was wrapped in absorbent acid pads and taped around the valve to capture any product that might discharge.  Per the car owner, the car is to be set out so a mobile repair unit can change the bolts and flange gasket.

column168: As the freight was being removed from a trailer at the destination terminal, a forklift operator punctured the drum causing material to be released to the trailer floor. The drum was immediately placed into an overpack container to prevent further release of material. The released material was absorbed and contents were place into the overpack container for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This incident was caused by operator error while operating the forklift. The employee was disciplined and re-trained per company policy on the importance of following proper forklift operating procedures. This incident may be used in future training discussion or safety topics to illustrate the importance of following proper forklift procedures.

column168: On 02/28/20 at 22:45 Hours it was reported by the Palmer MA. Police dispatch center that emergency response personnel were out on CSX property near the crossing at Main ST and the railroad bridge Palmer MA. With a smell of gas in the area. It later determined that was it was coming from railcars that had been placed at interchange from the New England Railroad. Palmer Police, Fire, MA state hazmat and Mass DEP where already on site. No visible product was leaking from the 12 railcars of UN2448 Sulphur Molten, but there was low detectable levels of hydrogen Sulfide present on their four gas meter in the area of the railcars.     HEPACO a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the area and found the following 7 railcars with the below listed defects. ITDX 7181 was found with the use of a H2S meter to be having a vapor release from the area of the manway and the rupture disk area. The manway was opened and found to be leaking from an improperly tightened manway and improperly installed manway gasket. The gasket was reinstalled correctly retightened. A vapor leak was also located coming from the rupture disk of the pressure relief device. Disk was not damaged but was leaking vapor. The rupture disk was removed and found to have excessive dried product build up behind the disk causing it not to seal properly. Disk was cleaned and reinstalled with no further issue.      ITDX 6928 – was found with the use of a H2S meter to be having a vapor release from the area of the manway. It was found that the manway was not properly secured for transportation. The manway was opened to check the integrity of the gasket. It was in good condition. Hardened sulfur product was removed from both the gasket and nozzle surface before securing the manway. The manway bolts where tightened and no further issues found.  ITDX 6933 – was found with the use of a H2S meter to be having a vapor release from the area of the manway. It was observed that the manway was not properly secured. The manway was opened to check the integrity of the gasket. It was found to be in good condition. The manway bolt assemblies was lubricated and retightened. It was also found with the use of a H2S meter that the railcar was also having a vapor release from the area of the rupture disk. The crew observed three (3) gaskets under the disk (2 Teflon, 1 Rubber). The gasket seat was cleaned and the rupture disk was reinstalled with proper gasket. No leak was detected afterwards. ITDX 6939 – With the use of a H2S meter a leak was located from the rupture disk. Upon inspection the rupture disk was found to have 2 Teflon gasket installed was causing it to leak. The disk was cleaned and reinstalled with proper Gasket. No further defects where noted with the railcar.  ITDX 6960 –It was found with the use of a H2S meter to be having a vapor release from the area of the manway. It was observed that that manway was not properly secured. The crew opened the manway to check the integrity of the gasket. It was

column168: Heritage Transport driver arrived at customer site (Republic Conduit, Inc.) to unload a waste acid tank inside their building in a contained area. He hooked-up his tanker hose to the customer’s acid tank. He also hooked-up a vent hose going from the truck to a plastic 55 gallon drum. After determining everything was hooked up properly, the driver started the transfer. The driver subsequently observed foam being released from the vent hose onto the floor. The driver immediately stopped the transfer. He inspected both fittings (the tank and the truck) and determined that one of the seals needed changed. He changed the seal to the truck's fitting, and then finished the tank transfer with no further issues. The release lasted about seven to ten minutes and approximately twenty gallons of product was released onto the concrete floor. The release happened in a contained area and absorbent mats were used to clean-up the product on the floor. It was determined that air got into the line through a bad connection. The tank had a plastic fitting on it that was somewhat worn. The tanker had a stainless steel fitting on it and the plastic fitting wouldn't consistently seal properly.
column169: Heritage Transport and Republic Conduit management worked together on the investigation and corrective actions to prevent any future occurrences.Republic Conduit replaced the plastic fitting on their tank with a stainless steel fitting. This will assure a much better seal with the Heritage Transport truck's stainless steel fitting.

On February 13, 2020, at 0654 hours, CSX FG Train Dispatcher advised that the K42911, loaded unit train of Alcohols, NOS, had derailed at Mile Post CMG 123.8 of the Kingsport Subdivision.  CSX immediately responded personnel and contractors from several departments- including the CSX Hazardous Materials Team.  It was subsequently discovered the cause of the derailment was a mud/rock slide which over ran the tracks was struck by the east bound K42911.  This caused the three locomotives and line one through five of the consist to derail.  Damage incurred during the derailment caused tank cars TILX 194769 (line three) and TILX 192469 (line four) to rupture and release product.  The released product, in addition to fuel and oil release from the locomotives, caught fire and was released into the Big Sandy River.  Additional fuel, oil, and Alcohols, NOS, that were not release and/or burned were removed from the derailment site and shipped for proper recycling and/or disposal.  Additionally, all cars, debris, and to the extent possible, contaminated soils, were removed from the site to allow for restoration of the railroad tracks.  At current time, CSX continue remediate the environmental impact and mitigate an ongoing mud/rock slide risk.

column168: HF driver team was in the process of unloading T-778 at customer site when they noticed a wisp of product emitting from the 1" plug on top of the unloading hose tee. The unloading activity was stopped, and the hose cleared. The plug was tightened, and the unloading activity resumed without issue.  The plug should only be removed by operators during their unloading hose pressure test.  Before the plug is reinstalled, pipe thread sealant is to be applied.  When the plug was removed after the tank returned to Geismar, there was no evidence that the thread sealant had been applied the last time the plug was installed.
column169: Due to the standard not being followed on this occasion, operators are being retrained on the importance on using thread sealant and properly tightening the plug after leak testing.

WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED TRAILER DOORS TO CHECK LOAD AT THE TA, LIQUID SPILLED OUT THE BACK OF TRAILER ONTO GRASSY/DIRT AREA WHERE THE TRAILER WAS BACKED UP IN A PARKING SPOT. HE CLOSED THE DOORS BUT LIQUID WAS STILL COMING OUT THE BACK. DRIVER ESTIMATED 5 GALS. OR MORE WAS RELEASED. TRAILER FLOOR WAS COVERED WITH STANDING LIQUID.  HAZ-MAT ONE WAS CALLED, CLOSET RESPONSE TEAM, TAS ENVIRONMENTAL, WAS 4.5 HRS. OUT. TA WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO UPON ARRIVAL, INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO MOVE HIS TRAILER TO THE PAVEMENT. THEY PUT SPEEDY DRY IN BACK OF TRAILER AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE PAVEMENT WHERE LIQUID WAS STILL COMING OUT. THEY SECURED THE SITUATION AS BEST AS POSSIBLE AND LEFT, TAKING THE CONTAINMENT ABSORBENTS WITH THEM.  THE FOLLOWING DAY, TAS ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED ON SCENE. MORE MATERIAL BY NOW HAD RELEASED ONTO THE PAVEMENT, EST. 10 GALS, DUE TO BAGS CONTINUING TO LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL BAGS ON BOARD WERE LEAKING AT THE SEAMS. BADS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO 2 ROLL-OFF BOXES AND TAKEN TO THE TSDF FOR DISPOSAL. CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM ORIGINAL PARKED LOCATION WAS ALSO REMEDIATED AND PUT IN THE ROLL OFFS, ALONG WITH CLEANUP MATERIAL USED TO REMEDIATE THE TRAILER FLOOR AND PAVEMENT.
column169: THE SHIPPER RECOGNIZED THAT THE BAGS FOR THIS MATERIAL ARE NOT SUITED TO TRANSPORT THIS MATERIAL.  THEY ARE WORKING ON UTILIZING ANOTHER TYPE OF BAG WITH INNER LINER(S).

column168: On February 27,2020, at approximately 1:00 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers(RLC) observed a damaged bag on trailer OA7460 at the above-referenced location at door 138. As a result of the damage, approximately 4 ounces of UN1727 Ammonium Hydrogendifluoride was released to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched Hazmat Special Services(HSS) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, crews noted one(1) bag of ammonium hydrogendifluoride that was damaged with a tear on the top of the bag. It appeared the damage took place during the loading process. The damaged bag was removed for disposal and crews utilized hand tools to collect approximately 4 ounces of released product. All ammonium hydrogenfluoride impacted material and one(1) damaged bag were collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. HSS personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

column168: Driver was traveling on US-23 when he noticed smoke coming from the rear of the unit.  Driver stopped and investigated. The tire on the trailer was on fire. Driver called 911 and attempted to put out the fire. The automatic closing device worked as designed. As the fire continued to burn, the automatic closing device received external damage, causing a small product release to the air. We estimated 10 liquid gallons. Once the fire was extinguished, the product was transferred to another trailer and the road was reopened.
column169: Root cause analysis completed with no underlying corrective issues discovered. Cause was a tire fire.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted an odor coming from tank car NATX 32599 (Residue / Dimethylamine Anhydrous / UN 1032) during switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, La. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting odor coming from around NATX 33259.  The housing seal was removed, and valves were checked and the A end liquid valve was found to be partially open and the plug was less than tool tight. The valve was closed and the plug was tightened, the leak stopped.  A new security seal was applied. Tank car was released for movement.

2020/02/23 03:00 CN transportation Battle Creek, MI reported odor coming from car TEVX 84432 UN2927 Class 6.1// (8) Toxic Liquid, Corrosive, ORGANIC, N.O.S., (2,4,Dichlorophenol) car was isolated CN Yard Battle Creek, MI . All appropriate departments notified, CN DGO responded finding tank car leaking vapor from protective housing area. Air monitoring performed, none detected (Product has very low odor threshold). CN contractor responded to assist with securement of car finding liquid valves and pressure plate leaking vapor. Contractor pulled vacuumed on car and it held (-8 PSI) for 4 days. Car returned to RP Midland MI.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On Sunday,  February 23, 2020, tank car CBTX 735069 was loaded with diesel fuel. The following day there was approximately 1 gallon of product released from the 3in to 1 in reducer bushing that connects the sample line to the pressure plate. The release was due to the 3 in bushing not being properly secure to the pressure plate. While we were leak testing the car we also found that there was a leak from the 3 in liquid line ball valve and air was releasing around the ball likely due to normal wear.
column169: The bushing was re-taped and properly secured. The 3 in ball valve was replaced. The car was re leaked tested after the repairs were made and there were no leaks found.

column43: Evaporator Solids with Trace Barium, Lead
column168: While unloading a truck at the Veolia 10 day in-transit facility in Tonawanda, NY, Veolia employees  noticed a small liquid spot on the floor of the truck. The employees located the leaking drum and over packed it into an 851A2 drum. Approximately 5 ounces of the sludge material leaked from the bottom seam of the 55 gallon drum. The Veolia employees that picked up the drum from the customer site did inspect the drum prior to accepting it for transportation. It was about 3 hours back to the Veolia office from the customer site to when they noticed the drum leaking from the bottom seam.
column169: Veolia will review this incident during the next training class to bring awareness to this scenario to help prevent this type of spill from reoccurring in the future. There will be an emphasis on thoroughly  inspecting drums and containers prior to accepting for transportation.

column168: On February 14, 2020, at 0226 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal UBU regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to blocking and bracing, (4) 1-gallon plastic jugs of Birko Purple Marking Paint (Ethanol, solution, flammable, UN1170) were damaged, releasing approximately 4 gallons of product on to the trailer floor.  Terminal personnel cleaned up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged jugs, spent absorbents and all other waste debris were containerized in (1) 10-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: The Petro Chemical Transport, LLC driver was attempting to deliver diesel fuel into the customers storage tank. The driver failed to connect all of the necessary hoses to the storage tank. column168: As driver was approaching a stop light to turn left onto an on-ramp, the light turned green and he did not come to a complete stop and started the corner at 8 mph. He took the corner a little wide and the front axle tire went up on the curb. This ramp has a slight slope to it. From the slope, not coming to complete stop and hitting the curb these events caused the load to shift enough to rollover. The police did not issue citation and deemed it is due to unfamiliarity with this ramp.
column169: Additional training was provided including Tanker Solutions (Vehicle Inspection and Driving Techniques) and Rollover prevention. These included videos, review and a quiz. column168: A fiberboard box was discovered containing 4 plastic bottles of Instant Hand Sanitizer Antiseptic Gel with Moisturizers and Emollients manufactured by Quality Chemical, each with net quantity of 3.785 L. The shipment was discovered at the OXRA origin station in Ventura, CA USA and was being shipped to China. There were no DG markings or labeling on the package, and no Shippers Declaration was offered with the shipment. The contents of the bottles were not leaking, no spill was involved. The origin station indicated the shipper had attempted to send same shipment twice before, but it had been rejected both times as misdeclared DG because in those instances the packaging that was used had a Ground Limited Quantity mark on it. The package in the current shipment'does not have the Ground Limited Quantity mark affixed.

column168: A package containing a plastic Jerrican overpacked inside a fiberboard box was discovered leaking during PM sort operations at the MEMH hub. The package was part of a 6-piece shipment, but only one piece was observed leaking. The commodity in the jerrican was UN1760 Corrosive Liquid n.o.s.(SODIUM SULPHITE) packing group III. The seal on the top closure of the jerrican was observed broken and the cap was loose, resulting in the leak. The spill was confined to the package in the sort area and did not enter a drain. Following cleanup by FedEx Spill Cleanup staff, the package was contained in salvage packaging. An amended Shipper's Declaration for Dangerous Goods was received from the shipper, and subsequently the involved package was returned to the shipper.

column168: On February 26,2020, at approximately 1:40 pm CST, a tractor-trailer being operated by R+L Carriers(RLC) was parked at the above-referenced location when the unit's driver observed a leak within the unit's trailer due to a nail puncturing one(1) 15-gallon pale. As a result, approximately 8 gallons of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide was released to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew fr6m E3 Environmental(E3) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, crews noticed a nail from a pallet that punctured a 15-gallon pale of potassium hydroxide and release approximately 8 gallons to the trailer floor. E3 personnel applied a neutralizing agent to the release product then deployed granular absorbents to the trailer floor and worked them in with hand tools. The damaged pale was removed for disposal. All potassium hydroxide impacted material and the damaged pale were collected and containerized in two(2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. E3 personnel noted not further actions were required on-site and crews demobilized.

Driver stated that prior to unloading the operator was switching over from totes to offloading,  Driver shut off the internal vale, but the operator left the valve open on top of the tote to drain the  hose, and it overflowed the tote.  About 10-15 gals of Dabco T Catalyst Spilled into concrete  containment.  The Customer is handling cleanup.
column169: This was a Customer related issue.  Driver was counseled on communicating with external operators and ensuring valves are shut.

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver failed to follow his routine and did not connect the drop gun to the ground fitting before opening the internal valve. He realized the mistake immediately and closed the valve after losing 11 gallons.  Driver and one QT employee cleaned the spill and waited till the concrete dried and was released by QT and safety.
column169: Driver was retrained on proper unloading procedures and the importance of sticking with the routine.

column168: Motorist alleged that one of our trailers was apparently leaking as there was a very foul odor coming from it.  He did not have the complete trailer #, but after some research it was determined to be Trailer 516902. It was also raining. EMI was contacted. Transload will probably occur.  Cleanup crew in route with chemical pads, plastic and duct tape, crew will diaper trailer and follow driver to MOBL, AL.  Driver will be put up in a  hotel for the night.  Clean up crew arrived and could find no leak.  They did find some product in the crash box and that the dome lid was not tightened down properly.  The crash box was cleaned (5 gallon can) and they were going to follow the unit to the Mobile terminal to make sure nothing was leaking.
column169: Additional training was given to the Driver on how to ensure all lids/valves are secure.

column42: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: During x-ray scans or package freight at the NRRBC location at Luis Munoz Marin Intl Airport in Carolina, Puerto Rico, two inbound FedEx Paks were identified as containing aerosol cans. Further investigation showed the Paks each contained one 12 oz can of Affresh Stainless Steel Cleaning Spray distributed by Whirlpool Corporation. Per the SDS document associated with the product, this commodity is classified as Division 2.1 dangerous goods, specifically UN1950, AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE. There were no Dangerous Goods markings or labels on the packages, and no Shippers Declarations for Dangerous Goods were provided. The involved FedEx Paks were individual shipments associated with tracking numbers 815238752905 and 815238753500. The packages were offered for shipment by the Whirlpool Corp office in Guaynabo, PR to two separate residential addresses in Caguas, PR. The station was. directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to hold the packages pending further disposition instruction.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: 2/24/2020, 11:43-Trailer 337was located with 44,860 lbs of 42% Sulfuric Acid Solution. 2/25/20,  Trailer 337 departed the Future Fuel Plant-6:11 am -Trailer 337 impacted a extreme rough spot on the highway at a bridge and the tanker immediately ruptured spilling the entire contents. Other vehicles are contaminated with the acid. One vehicles loses control impacts barrier cables in median.  6:12am -Driver calls 911  6:25 am- Hwy 167 is closed , north and south bound 7:19am - E3 response  arrives on site  8:45 am- the National Response Center is notified 11:45am- The driver is administered a DOT Drug/Alcohol test 12:55 pm- The accident scene is declared "neutralized" 3:30pm- E3 departs site. See additional page for more information.
column169: At this time, we do not know the failure mechanism that caused the tank to rupture.  We do not believe it was corrosion related.  The tank had been properly inspected and tested per 49 CFR Part 180.407.  We are continuing our investigation into the cause for the tank rupture and will take necessary actions to prevent recurrence.
